## `LockManager.ofd_lock(self, inode: int, fd_id: int, op: LockOp, start: int, length: int, *, wait: bool = False) -> None`
<!-- checksum: locks-4 -->

### Purpose
Acquire / release OFD lock. Scoped by `fd_id` (open-file-description) rather than pid. Two fds in the same process conflict with each other's OFD locks.

### Preconditions
Same as `posix_lock` (minus `pid`).

### Postconditions
- Exactly `posix_lock` semantics but with `owner=fd_id` and `kind="ofd"`. Compare conflict against other `kind="ofd"` records only.
- Releasing an fd via `on_fd_close` removes only that fd's OFD records.

### Test Strategy
`test_locks Â§ test_ofd_*` (2 tests).

---

## `LockManager.flock(self, inode: int, fd_id: int, op: FlockOp, *, wait: bool = False) -> None`
<!-- checksum: locks-5 -->

### Purpose
BSD whole-file advisory lock. Scoped by `fd_id`. No byte ranges â€” always covers the whole file.

### Preconditions
- `op` is one of `"shared"`, `"exclusive"`, `"unlock"`.

### Postconditions
- Records have `start=0, length=0` always (full file, to EOF).
- Conflict rules: exclusive conflicts with any other; shared conflicts only with exclusive.
- `on_fd_close(inode, fd_id, _pid)` releases this fd's flock records.

### Test Strategy
`test_locks Â§ test_flock_*` (2 tests).

